01:53.593 --> 02:01.821
fascinating. namely studies of sedimentation in 
the past by using the type of deposit that occurs in

02:02.257 --> 02:31.690
the glacial strata around Scandinavia, where you 
can distinguish every single year and therefore

02:02.257 --> 02:31.690
establish a chronology and study processes on an 
absolute time basis. How do you distinguish every

02:32.041 --> 02:33.483
year? Does it fall in layers like, you mean like a 
tree reversed? Exactly like tree rings,

02:36.628 --> 02:54.758
essentially, because in spring you get the flood, 
the melting, and that gives rise to a specific type

02:36.628 --> 02:54.758
of more coarse grain deposit, and in winter and 
fall and winter, things slow down and the

02:36.628 --> 02:54.758
character of the sediment, chemical character of 
sediment is different. So therefore you get the

02:55.279 --> 02:58.504
kind of tree ring-like effect, and you can measure 
the thicknesses of these rings, and therefore

02:58.906 --> 03:19.204
seek to reconstruct exactly the

02:58.906 --> 03:19.204
different hydrologic conditions and metrologic 
conditions during each year, and also use this

02:58.906 --> 03:19.204
sequence as a timekeeper and measure things on an 
absolute time basis. Is that what began the

03:19.484 --> 03:23.267
Scandinavian's interest in deep sea drilling? I 
wouldn't say so. So the deposits of this kind were

03:28.167 --> 03:43.143
